      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fending Off the Yangtze</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Worldwatch Institute president, Lester R Brown, agrees with August 23 editorial urging Chinese Government to forgo Three Gorges dam project and to devote estimated $50 billion it will cost to more effective flood management strategies on Yangtze River (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Managing Flood Waters in China'' (editorial, Aug. 23): As you suggest, it is time to forgo the Three Gorges dam project and devote the estimated $50 billion it will cost to  ''more effective flood management strategies'' on the Yangtze River..</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Managing Flood Waters in China'' (editorial, Aug. 23): As you suggest, it is time to forgo the Three Gorges dam project and devote the estimated $50 billion it will cost to  ''more effective flood management strategies'' on the Yangtze River..</p>
        <p>While floods are almost always classified as natural disasters, human activities have clearly intensified the recent flooding. The Yangtze basin is one of the most densely populated in the world. Intensive land development and widespread deforestation have  undermined the water-holding capacity of the watershed.</p>
        <p>Although China has announced logging restrictions in the basin, development in the flood plains and the draining of lakes that hold overflow continue.</p>
        <p>LESTER R. BROWN  Washington, Aug. 24, 1998  The writer is president of the Worldwatch Institute.</p>
      </block>
